In my bathroom, I peeled the bandage off. The stitches held. *Rosa.* The name echoed through the years. Mother’s suicide when I was six—a “tragic fall” from their bedroom window. Father’s “accident” last spring, skull cracked open on museum steps. Coincidences were for fools, and I’d stopped being one the day I found his bloody notebook hidden in the icebox.  

I poured bourbon, lit a cigarette, and stared at the manifest. Midnight had passed. The throne was still missing. But the trail wasn’t cold—it was burning.  

———  

The museum’s night guard let me in after hours. Joe’s keys jangled as we slipped into Gallery 17, his loyalty bought with a bottle of Canadian whiskey and the promise I’d never mention his brother’s arrest last fall. I knelt by the pedestal, flashlight beam catching a glint in the mortar—a shard of lapis lazuli. Prussian blue.  

Joe whistled. “Tunnels under the museum. Rumor is they connect to the docks.”  

*Follow the blue.* The phrase pulsed, insistent. I palmed the stone. “Show me.”  

He hesitated, sweat beading under his cap. “Your old man asked the same thing. Week before he died.”  

The air thickened. “And?”  

“Told him the same as I’ll tell you.” He turned toward the service elevator. “Watch your step.”  

———  

The tunnels smelled of wet earth and iron. Joe’s flashlight carved shaky circles ahead. Graffiti marked the walls—crude arrows, cryptic symbols, a faded *R* inside a circle. My thumb traced the lighter in my pocket. *Rosa. Rosalind. Red.*  

We emerged near the docks, moonlight staining the Hudson silver. Joe gripped my arm. “This is where I clock out.”  

Alone, I followed the *R*s chalked on crates until I reached a warehouse door ajar. Inside, dust motes swam in shafts of light. A single crate sat center floor.  

No throne. Just a faded playbill: *ROSALIND’S FOLLY, 1912.* Mother’s stage name glared up at me, her face blurred under decades of grime.  

———  

Vito found me at the Blind Owl’s bar. “Pier 17 was a decoy,” I said, sliding the playbill toward him.  

He studied it, thumb brushing the date. “Rosa’s been dead years. Why dredge her up now?”  

“Same reason they’re using my father’s initials. This isn’t about art.”  

He ordered two whiskeys. “It’s about blood.”  

We drank in silence, shoulders almost touching. The phonograph crooned *Nobody knows you when you’re down and out.*  

“The tunnels connect to the museum,” I said. “Someone’s using them. Moving more than thrones.”  

Vito’s smile cut sharp. “Careful, Red. Ghosts bite.”  

I slid off the stool. “So do I.”  

